  "description": "The two-component Norton power law (Norton 1929) is commonly used to model the creep behavior of salt. The standard form of this law is (1) \\[\\dot \\epsilon_{cr} = A\\ \\bar \\sigma^n\\] where \\(\\dot \\epsilon_{cr}\\) is the creep rate, \\(A\\) and \\(n\\) are material properties, and \\(\\bar \\sigma\\) is the von Mises stress. By definition, \\(\\bar \\sigma = \\sqrt{3J_2}\\) , and \\(J_2\\) is the second invariant of the effective deviatoric-stress tensor, \\(\\sigma_{ij}^d\\) (i.e., \\(J_2 = {1 \\over 2} \\sigma_{ij}^d \\sigma_{ij}^d\\) ). The deviatoric stress increments are given by (2) \\[\\Delta \\sigma_{ij}^{d} = 2G",
